Feature selection part¶

Outlier Removal¶

All data outside of 1.5 times the IQR (Inter-Quartile Range) are usually considered to be outliers. However, removing all transactions outside of 1.5 times the IQR would dramatically decrease our training data size, which is not very large, to begin with. Thus, I decided to only focus on extreme outliers outside of 2.5 times the IQR.

In [13]:
df_bill = df[['BILL_AMT1','BILL_AMT2','BILL_AMT3','BILL_AMT4','BILL_AMT5','BILL_AMT6']]
In [14]:
#Only removing extreme outliers
Q1 = df_bill.quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df_bill.quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

df2 = df[~((df_bill < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) |(df_bill > (Q3 + 1.5* IQR))).any(axis=1)]

def normalize(X):
    """
    Make the distribution of the values of each variable similar by subtracting the mean and by dividing by the standard deviation.
    """
    for feature in X.columns:
        X[feature] -= X[feature].mean()
        X[feature] /= X[feature].std()
    return X

#normalize df
df_f = normalize(df_f)

Visualizing our classes show us if they are clearly separable and with t-SNE, we can project these higher dimensional distributions into lower-dimensional visualizations. Instead of directly using all features, we select 6 most significant features, which are "PAY_0","PAY_2","PAY_3","PAY_4","PAY_5","PAY_6". In the plot, we can see that fraud data points tend to cluster together, however, some of the fraud data also in that cluster too. It shows that the classifiers may not behave very well since there is no direct boundary and we should carefully choose complexity parameters.

def cv_eval( max_d, min_leaf, x_train, y_train ):
    dt_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', max_depth=max_d, min_samples_leaf=min_leaf)
    cv10_acc = np.mean(cross_val_score(dt_clf, x_train, y_train, cv=10)) 

    return cv10_acc

F score

The F score is the weighted harmonic mean of precision and recall, reaching its optimal value at 1 and its worst value at 0. The beta parameter determines the weight of precision in the combined score. < 1 lends more weight to precision, while > 1 favors recall. Because both precision and recall are equally important to the accuracy of the model, the F-1 score, or F score when is set to 1, was used. The equation of F score can be represented by Equation .

$$precision = \frac{TP}{TP + FP}$$$$F_\beta = (1 + \beta^2) \frac{\text{precision} \times \text{recall}}{\beta^2 \text{precision} + \text{recall}}.$$

Spot-checking algorithms¶

Spot-checking algorithms is a part of the process of applied machine learning. On a new problem, you need to quickly determine which type or class of algorithms is good at picking out the structure in your problem and which are not.

In [76]:
##Spot-Checking Algorithms
models = []

models.append(('Logreg', LogisticRegression()))
models.append(('Dec Tree', DecisionTreeClassifier()))
models.append(('KNN', KNeighborsClassifier()))
models.append(('K', BaggingClassifier(KNeighborsClassifier())))
models.append(('SVM',svm.SVC()))
models.append(('T', BaggingClassifier(tree.DecisionTreeClassifier())))
models.append(('Ran For', RandomForestClassifier()))

#testing models

results = []
names = []

for name, model in models:
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=10, scoring='roc_auc')
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = '%s: %f (%f)' % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)
